04813nam a22007695i 9780812293005DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162016pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979910580  a97808122930057 a10.9783/97808122930052doi  a(DE-B1597)469696  a(OCoLC)951076737  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0360202bisacsh1 aFuentes, Marisa J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDispossessed Lives :bEnslaved Women, Violence, and the Archive /cMarisa J. Fuentes. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b8 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEarly American Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Jane: Fugitivity, Space, and Structures of Control in Bridgetown -- tChapter 2. Rachael and Joanna: Power, Historical Figuring, and Troubling Freedom -- tChapter 3. Agatha: White Women, Slave Owners, and the Dialectic of Racialized Gender -- tChapter 4. Molly: Enslaved Women, Condemnation, and Gendered Terror -- tChapter 5. “Venus”: Abolition Discourse, Gendered Violence, and the Archive -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the eighteenth century, Bridgetown, Barbados, was heavily populated by both enslaved and free women. Marisa J. Fuentes creates a portrait of urban Caribbean slavery in this colonial town from the perspective of these women whose stories appear only briefly in historical records. Fuentes takes us through the streets of Bridgetown with an enslaved runaway; inside a brothel run by a freed woman of color; in the midst of a white urban household in sexual chaos; to the gallows where enslaved people were executed; and within violent scenes of enslaved women's punishments. In the process, Fuentes interrogates the archive and its historical production to expose the ongoing effects of white colonial power that constrain what can be known about these women.Combining fragmentary sources with interdisciplinary methodologies that include black feminist theory and critical studies of history and slavery, Dispossessed Lives demonstrates how the construction of the archive marked enslaved women's bodies, in life and in death. By vividly recounting enslaved life through the experiences of individual women and illuminating their conditions of confinement through the legal, sexual, and representational power wielded by slave owners, colonial authorities, and the archive, Fuentes challenges the way we write histories of vulnerable and often invisible subjects.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aSlaveryzCaribbean AreaxHistoryvSources. 0aSlaveryzCaribbean AreaxHistory. 0aWomen slaveszCaribbean AreavBiography. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aGender Studies.  aWomen's Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2016z9783110485189oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066591840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229300540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812293005423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812293005.jpg  a978-3-11-066591-8  University of Pennsylvania Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17S